cophone audiences and transformed the lives and labor of many African American musicians, who found financial and personal success as well as discrimination in France. By showing how the popularity of African American music was intertwined with contemporary structures of racism and imperialism, Moore demonstrates this music's centrality to postwar France and the convergence of decolonization, the expanding globalized economy, the Cold War, and worldwide liberation movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAfrican American musicianszFrance. 0aAfrican AmericansvMusicxInfluence. 0aAfrican AmericanszFrancexMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aBlues (Music)zEuropexHistory and criticism. 0aBlues (Music)zFrancey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJazzzEuropexHistory and criticism. 0aJazzzFrancey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPopular musiczEuropexHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Jazz.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021995zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021995/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles